1 Sec. 12. 1. On or before July 1, 2026, the Board shall
2 establish and submit to the Commissioner a plan of operation for
3 the FAIR Plan which satisfies the requirements of sections 2 to 18,
4 inclusive, of this act. The plan of operation and any amendments
5 to the plan of operation become effective upon written approval of
6 the Commissioner.
7 2. The plan of operation for the FAIR Plan must provide for:
8 (a) The lines of insurance coverage which are to be written.
9 (b) Coverage limits for:
10 (1) Property insurance, in an amount which must be
11 $750,000 or less; and
12 (2) Commercial property insurance, in an amount which
13 must be $5,000,000 or less.
14 (c) The policy forms which are to be used.
15 (d) The perils which are to be covered.
16 (e) The establishment of reasonable standards for
17 underwriting to determine the eligibility of a risk, which must
18 include the requirement that coverage under the FAIR Plan is
19 only available if:
20 (1) A fire risk assessment is conducted on the property to be
21 covered and the property owner implements the findings and
22 recommendations for mitigation set forth in the assessment.
23 (2) During the 2 years immediately preceding the date on
24 which the coverage begins, not less than three authorized insurers
25 have declined to issue a policy of property insurance or
26 commercial property insurance, as applicable, which covers the
27 property; and
28 (3) During each 2-year period in which the property is
29 covered by the FAIR Plan, the owner of the property applies to not
30 less than three authorized insurers for a policy of property
31 insurance or commercial property insurance, as applicable, to
32 cover the property and each authorized insurer to which the owner
33 applies declines to issue such a policy.
34 (f) Any compensation or commission which is to be paid to a
35 producer of insurance who offers the FAIR Plan.
36 (g) Procedures for the collection of fees, including the times at
37 which fees will be collected, from Association members.
38 (h) Assessments against Association members, which must be
39 in the proportion that the premiums received by each assessed
40 Association member bear to premiums received for all assessed
41 Association members, for the 3 most recent calendar years for
42 which such information is available. As used in this paragraph,
43 “premiums received” means premiums received on property
44 insurance lines and commercial property insurance lines in this
45 State.
